<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<%- include('../partials/head', { title: 'Authentication & Security' }) %>

    <body>
        <%- include('../partials/sidebar', { activePage: 'authentication' }) %>

            <main class="main-content">
                <div class="content-container">

                    <header class="hero-banner">
                        <span class="badge">Security</span>
                        <h1>Authentication & Access Control</h1>
                        <p>Learn how users sign in, how invitations work, and how roles and permissions control access
                            across the portal.</p>
                    </header>

                    <ul class="breadcrumbs">
                        <li><a href="/docs">Docs</a></li>
                        <li class="current">Authentication</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="panel panel-info">
                        <div class="panel-title">Quick Summary</div>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Users access the portal by signing in with an email and password.</li>
                            <li>Admins provision users by sending an invitation with a unique, one-time token link.</li>
                            <li>Invited users must create a password before they can log in.</li>
                            <li>Access is controlled by <strong>Roles</strong>, and each role has a set of
                                <strong>Permissions</strong>.
                            </li>
                            <li>After inviting a user, an admin must explicitly assign roles for the user to have the
                                correct access.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="doc-section">
                        <h2>1. What Authentication Means in This Portal</h2>
                        <p>Authentication confirms who you are before you can access the Automation Portal. This portal
                            uses
                            a simple account model:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Email</strong> identifies your user account.</li>
                            <li><strong>Password</strong> is created during the invitation process.</li>
                            <li>Once your account is active, you can sign in and access features based on your assigned
                                roles.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <div class="panel panel-success">
                            <div class="panel-title">What Users Need to Know</div>
                            <ul>
                                <li>You cannot log in until you complete the invitation and set your password.</li>
                                <li>If you can sign in but cannot see a feature, it usually means your role does not
                                    include
                                    permission for it.</li>
                                <li>If you believe you should have access, contact an admin to review your roles.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="doc-section">
                        <h2>2. Roles & Permissions (How Access Works)</h2>
                        <p>Access to features in the portal is controlled using <strong>roles</strong> and
                            <strong>permissions</strong>.
                        </p>

                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Role</strong>: A named access profile assigned to a user (example: User, Admin,
                                Super Admin).</li>
                            <li><strong>Permission</strong>: A specific ability granted by a role (example: view
                                responses,
                                manage forms, access configuration).</li>
                        </ul>

                        <p>Users can have multiple roles. Their effective access is based on the combined permissions
                            across
                            their roles.</p>

                        <div class="panel panel-warning">
                            <div class="panel-title">Important</div>
                            <p>Inviting a user does not automatically assign roles. An admin must explicitly edit the
                                user
                                and add roles after the invitation.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="doc-section">
                        <h2>3. End User: First-Time Login (Invitation Flow)</h2>
                        <p>New users are created through an invitation email. The invite includes a unique token link
                            that
                            allows the user to set their password.</p>

                        <h3>Step-by-Step: Accept Invitation and Create Password</h3>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Open the invitation email sent by the Automation Portal.</li>
                            <li>Click the invite link (this link contains a unique token tied to your account).</li>
                            <li>On the password setup screen, create your password.</li>
                            <li>After setting your password successfully, return to the portal login page.</li>
                            <li>Log in using your email and the password you created.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <div class="panel panel-info">
                            <div class="panel-title">After Login</div>
                            <p>Your access depends on the roles assigned to your account. If you can log in but do not
                                see
                                expected pages or actions,
                                your roles may still need to be assigned or adjusted by an admin.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="doc-section">
                        <h2>4. Admin Guide: Provisioning Users</h2>
                        <p>Admins and Super Admins can provision users through the <strong>Configuration</strong>
                            section.
                            Provisioning includes:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Inviting the user (creates the account and sends the invite email)</li>
                            <li>Assigning roles (grants access permissions)</li>
                            <li>Confirming the user is active and able to sign in</li>
                        </ul>

                        <div class="panel panel-info">
                            <div class="panel-title">Where to Manage Users</div>
                            <p>Navigate to <strong>Configuration</strong> and open the <strong>Users</strong> tab.</p>
                        </div>

                        <h3>4.1 Step-by-Step: Invite a New User</h3>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Go to <strong>Configuration</strong>.</li>
                            <li>Open the <strong>Users</strong> tab.</li>
                            <li>Click <strong>Invite User</strong>.</li>
                            <li>Enter the user’s <strong>Display Name</strong> and <strong>Email</strong>.</li>
                            <li>Submit the invite.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <p>The system sends an invitation email to the user with a unique token link to create a
                            password.
                        </p>

                        <div class="panel panel-warning">
                            <div class="panel-title">Critical Admin Step</div>
                            <p>After inviting a user, you must explicitly assign roles to the user. Without roles, the
                                user
                                may be able to log in
                                but will not have the access they need.</p>
                        </div>

                        <h3>4.2 Step-by-Step: Assign Roles After Inviting</h3>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Stay in <strong>Configuration</strong> → <strong>Users</strong>.</li>
                            <li>Find the user (use the search box if needed).</li>
                            <li>Click the <strong>Edit</strong> action for that user.</li>
                            <li>Add one or more <strong>Roles</strong> to the user.</li>
                            <li>Save the changes.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <p>Once roles are assigned, the user’s permissions are applied immediately based on the role
                            configuration.</p>

                        <h3>4.3 Step-by-Step: Validate Access</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Confirm the user status is <strong>Active</strong>.</li>
                            <li>Confirm the expected <strong>Roles</strong> are visible on the user record.</li>
                            <li>If the user reports missing access, review the role permissions in <strong>Roles &amp;
                                    Permissions</strong>.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <div class="panel panel-success">
                            <div class="panel-title">Recommended Provisioning Checklist</div>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Invite user (Display Name + Email)</li>
                                <li>User sets password via token link</li>
                                <li>Assign roles by editing the user</li>
                                <li>Verify role permissions match responsibility</li>
                                <li>Confirm user can access required sections</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="doc-section">
                        <h2>5. Admin Guide: Managing Roles & Permissions</h2>
                        <p>Roles define what users can see and do. Permissions are attached to roles, not directly to
                            users.
                        </p>

                        <h3>Best Practices</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Keep roles purpose-driven:</strong> create roles based on job function, not
                                individual users.</li>
                            <li><strong>Use least privilege:</strong> grant only the permissions required for the role.
                            </li>
                            <li><strong>Avoid overusing Super Admin:</strong> reserve it for system owners and
                                configuration
                                administrators.</li>
                            <li><strong>Review periodically:</strong> validate that roles still match responsibilities
                                as
                                the portal evolves.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <div class="panel panel-warning">
                            <div class="panel-title">Common Mistake</div>
                            <p>Inviting a user and assuming they can do their job immediately. If roles are not assigned
                                after the invite, the user will be blocked or see an incomplete portal.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="doc-section">
                        <h2>6. Developer Guide (Integration Notes)</h2>
                        <p>This section is for developers who extend the portal or integrate automations. It focuses on
                            how
                            to work safely with authentication and authorization behavior.</p>

                        <div class="panel panel-info">
                            <div class="panel-title">Core Rules</div>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Authentication verifies identity (email + password).</li>
                                <li>Authorization is role-based (roles grant permissions).</li>
                                <li>Do not assume “logged in” means “allowed.” Always enforce permission checks for
                                    protected actions.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>

                        <h3>Recommended Patterns</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Permission gating:</strong> hide UI actions when permission is missing, and
                                enforce
                                the same rule server-side.</li>
                            <li><strong>Stable access logic:</strong> base access checks on permissions, not display
                                text
                                labels.</li>
                            <li><strong>Auditability:</strong> log user actions for administrative operations (invites,
                                role
                                changes, status changes).</li>
                            <li><strong>Idempotency:</strong> treat invite operations and role updates carefully to
                                avoid
                                duplicates.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <div class="panel panel-success">
                            <div class="panel-title">Developer Checklist</div>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Every protected feature has a permission check</li>
                                <li>Role updates are reflected immediately and safely</li>
                                <li>Admin actions produce traceable logs</li>
                                <li>Error messages do not leak sensitive details</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="doc-section">
                        <h2>7. Troubleshooting & FAQs</h2>

                        <details class="accordion">
                            <summary>I invited a user but they cannot log in.</summary>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Confirm the user clicked the invite link and completed password setup.</li>
                                    <li>Confirm the user is <strong>Active</strong> in the Users list.</li>
                                    <li>If the token link expired, send a new invite (or follow your internal reset
                                        process
                                        if supported).</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </details>

                        <details class="accordion">
                            <summary>A user can log in but cannot see anything important.</summary>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <p>This is almost always a roles issue.</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Edit the user and confirm they have the correct roles assigned.</li>
                                    <li>Review <strong>Roles &amp; Permissions</strong> to confirm the role includes
                                        required permissions.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </details>

                        <details class="accordion">
                            <summary>What is the “unique token link” in the invite email?</summary>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <p>The invite email contains a one-time link tied to the user. It allows the user to
                                    securely create a password and activate login access.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>

                        <details class="accordion">
                            <summary>Do roles attach directly to users or to permissions?</summary>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <p>Roles are assigned to users. Permissions are attached to roles. Users receive
                                    permissions
                                    through their roles.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>

                        <details class="accordion">
                            <summary>Who should have Super Admin?</summary>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <p>Only system owners and administrators who must manage Configuration. For day-to-day
                                    operations, use Admin or purpose-specific roles where possible.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </main>
    </body>

</html>